Pour @water{300%ml}(cold and salted) into a #medium pot{} with a tight-fitting lid.

Stir in the @rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium, cover, and cook for ~{10%minutes}.

Remove the #pot{} from the heat.

Keep covered for ~rice{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to
cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @shallot{1}.

Trim the @green beans{150%g} then chop into thirds.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(clove) (or use a garlic press).

Roughly chop the @coriander{5%g}(stalks and all).

Place a #large pan{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once the pan is very hot, sear the @Irish beef strips{250%g} with the
@ground coriander{1%sachet} until cooked through, shifting as they colour,
~{2-3%minutes}. IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat and
its packaging. Meat is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Remove from the pan and set aside.

Return the pan to medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Add the shallot and cook until softened, stirring frequently, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir
in the garlic and @curry powder{2%sachets}. Cook for ~{1%minute}.

Pour in @water{100%ml} along with the @beef stock{1%sachet}.

Add the green beans, bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to medium.

Cover the pan with a lid or some foil and simmer until the green beans are
tender, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Once the green beans are tender, remove the lid from the pan and stir in the
@creme fraiche{110%g} and @cranberry chutney{1%sachet}.

Bring to the boil, then remove the pan from the heat.

Stir through the beef strips and half the coriander.

Taste and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} if desired.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and divide between bowls.

Top with the fruity beef curry.

Finish with a sprinkling of the remaining coriander.

> Fruitiness and curry may not be two concepts you would immediately put together,
> but in fact, they're a flavour pairing that really works! The fruitiness in
> this recipe comes from a helping of cranberry chutney, which also adds a
> pleasing sweetness to the dish.